questionTemplates.text:
M: Where were you today? I searched for you everywhere. I thought we could study together for tomorrow's quiz.
W: I went to the countryside. I forgot we would have the history quiz tomorrow. In fact, my trips to the countryside are few and far between.
{a}

W: Would you please spell your name?
M: Yes. It's W-I-double T-N-E-R.
{a}

W: Slow down. You are passing every car on the road.
M: Most drivers usually ignore the speed limit unless they think the police will stop them.
{a}

M: Hello. This is the most fascinating article I've ever come across. I think you should spare some time to read it.
W: Oh, really? I thought that anything about th election would be tedious.
{a}

M: Where've you been all this time? The train's about to leave!
W: I'm sorry I'm late, but I was waiting for you at the in formation desk. It's lucky I've found you here on the platform.
{a}

M: Do you like English?
F: Yes. But I think it's difficult to learn.
{a}

F: Now, would you show me your ticket?
M: Pardon?
{a}

M: Are men's suits on the seventh floor?
W: NO, they are here, on sixth. Seventh are house wares.
{a}

M: Can I see you at 10:00, Professor Brown?
W: I'm sorry, Charles, but I'm having class then. You should come see me half an hour later.
{a}

M: Now, what seems to be the trouble, Mrs. Black?
W: I've been coughing terribly recently, and last night I had some chest pain.
{a}

F: Peter, can I use your bike?
M: Sure, go ahead.
{a}

M: Will you please change this channel? I can't stand this program.
W: If you wait a minute, the news will be on next. I want to be sure to see it tonight.
{a}

W: Could you change a fifty-dollar bill?
M: Fifty? That would take all the change I've got.
{a}

F: Good morning. Can I help you?
M: Yes, please. May I borrow a book about English pronunciation?
{a}

M: Is there anything else you want to buy while we are downtown?
W: Let's stop at the camera shop to get some color film.
{a}

M: Jack speaks English well, doesn't he?
W: Yes. But Dick speaks English better than Jack, and Bob does even better than Dick.
{a}

M: Peter began to swim in 1980 and he joined a swimming club in 1982.
W: Yes, I know. He set a new world record in 1997.
{a}

M: What can we do that's free and fun?
W: Let's go to the history museum. Every first Sunday of the month, admission is free. That's tomorrow! Let's go.
{a}

F: How are you, Brenda?
M: Oh, dear, my back's killing me.
{a}

M: I just went to watch the sunrise at the seaside.
W: Why didn't you tell me? It's five years since I last saw it.
{a}

W: That seafood restaurant we went to last night is the best in town!
M: Isn't it, though!
{a}

M: It starts at half past seven, but let's meet at seven.
W: Ok, see you later.
{a}

M: Could I speak to Dr. Chen? She told me to call her today.
W: She's not available right now. Would you like to try around three?
{a}

W: What about your chemistry class this morning, Paul?
M: We were supposed to have a chemistry class but Mr. Anderson was out of town for a meeting, so we had a history lesson instead.
{a}

M: Would you like to see a menu?
W: No, thank you. I already know what I want to order.
{a}

M: Would you please help me with my English?
F: I'll be glad to. But I must finish the letter first.
{a}

W: Did you hear that the convenience store next to the gas station was held up last night?
M: Yes, I heard it on the radio this morning.
{a}

F: Dear, could you help me here a minute? I want to put the picture up.
M: OK, wily don't you cover the table, and I'll put it up.
{a}
